SIMPLE: whence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whence
<hw>Whence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>whennes</ets>, <ets>whens</ets> (with adverbial <it>s</it>,
properly a genitive ending; -- see <er>-wards</er>), also
<ets>whenne</ets>, <ets>whanene</ets>, AS. <ets>hwanan</ets>,
<ets>hwanon</ets>, <ets>hwonan</ets>, <ets>hwanone</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>when</ets>. See <er>When</er>, and cf. <er>Hence</er>,
<er>Thence</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>From what place; hence, from what or which source,
origin, antecedent, premise, or the like; how; -- used
interrogatively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Whence</qex> hath this man this wisdom?</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
xiii. 54.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Whence</qex> and what art thou?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>From what or which place, source, material, cause,
etc.; the place, source, etc., from which; -- used relatively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grateful to acknowledge <qex>whence</qex> his good⟦br⟧
Descends.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ All the words of this class, <xex>whence</xex>,
<xex>where</xex>, <xex>whither</xex>, <xex>whereabouts</xex>, etc., are
occasionally used as pronouns by a harsh construction.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, how unlike the place from <qex>whence</qex> they fell?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ <xex>From whence</xex>, though a pleonasm, is fully
authorized by the use of good writers.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>From whence</qex> come wars and fightings among you?</q>
<rj><qau>James iv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><xex>Of whence</xex>, also a pleonasm, has become
obsolete.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><ent>Whenceever</ent>⟦br⟧
